Hey guys! Got the second part of 'The Knight's Ward' for you. I'm hoping to get a chapter out per week.

https://pastebin.com/2kkkNe7r

A knight is sent to slay a bloodthirsty dragon but instead finds the beast in deep despair and longing for death. Unsure of whether or not to even attempt to carry out his mission, he seeks in the meantime to find out what ails it.

>The dragon woke up before me. I opened my eyes to see it unmoved from its previous position, though it stared directly at me through uninterested eyes. As though it had grown tired of everything inside its cave and I was just another thing added to the pile, immediately devoid of novelty.

>I drew myself up and sat crosslegged. From my belt I procured a piece of parchment and charred stick. Most people don't know it, but a knight is a skilled artist; he must be to sketch the lay of the land and report to his company commander how best to direct the flow of battle. When the commander is far from the front lines, his understanding of the battlefield entirely depends on the accuracy of his knights' drawings.

And yes the design description of the dragon is heavily inspired by that one photonoko image.

You got the right side of some of her features bigger than the left side. Her right ear is behind her head with that line there, but is bigger than the other despite giving the appearance of being at a slight distance away, and her right shoe's larger than the other. The hand shown has a long thumb, the position of the thumb is pointed down like a regular finger when it's normally limited to only pointing horizontally, and the two fingers pointing up round out to be larger than the rest of the finger going down to the palm. Aside from that, it's alright. Don't take any of that as me not liking it, just wanting to point out what I see's up with it.

If you're trying a simple, anime moe style, I'd try cross referencing other similar works to see what looks good with that sort of thing and trying to discover what makes it look good, or if you're going with a general cartoon style I'd recommend looking up general references with sketching features / limbs / etc and then trying to adapt that into your drawings. Even in the most cartoony of things, knowing how to draw realistically helps with everything. The thread isn't up, but there's sometimes a thread on improving drawing that I suggest you look into to see if it's up later on, and asking for suggestions to improve from there. Other tips I can give is continuing to practice, keep all of the old drawings you make no matter how bad or good they are, etc. I would also suggest keeping with the theme of the thread, but otherwise, keep going man.
